      • Alternative Spring Break

        Community Service - Community Service, A3C, Activities with Youth

        Mission

        Contact: Jason Cui, Artemis Xu

        Mission
        Alternative Spring Breaks @ Stanford
        Service. Learning. Social Change.

        Alternative Spring Breaks (ASB) @ Stanford are immersive service-learning programs that expose students to pressing social and cultural issues through community engagement, experiential education, direct service, group discussions, assigned readings, and reflective activities. The programs vision is to empower students to become informed advocates for social changelocally, nationally, and globally.

        ASB is a student-led Voluntary Student Organization (VSO) at Stanford University and an affiliate of the Haas Center for Public Service. As a proud Break Away Chapter Program, ASB would not be possible without the generous support of ASSU Special Fees.

        Impact
        Transforming students into lifelong advocates for social issues.

        ASB programs have inspired students to remain engaged with the social and cultural issues they exploreleading to the creation of student groups, the pursuit of new academic paths, and even long-term career shifts rooted in public service and social advocacy.

        History
        The first ASB trip took place in 1987, organized by staff at what was then the Public Service Center (now the Haas Center for Public Service). As student interest grew, ASB evolved into a registered, student-run organization. In 1996, a winter-quarter course was added to enhance learning ahead of the spring break trips.

        By the late 2000s, ASB expanded its reach:

        In 2008, Impact Abroad launched, offering global service-learning trips during the summer.

        In 2012, ThanksGiving Back was introduced as a new opportunity during Thanksgiving break.

        At its peak, ASB offered up to 18 courses and trips per year, continuing to be a transformative experience for hundreds of Stanford students.

        Recognition
        ASB has earned national acclaim from Break Away, including awards for:

        Alternative Spring Break Program of the Year

        Curriculum-Based Alternative Break of the Year

        At Stanford, ASB was honored with the Lyons Service Award in 1998 and an Outstanding Achievement Award from the Dean of Students in 2002. The program celebrated its 25th anniversary in 2012, marking a legacy of impact and leadership in public service education. In 2025, ASB was recognized by Stanford Report for the incredible programs and opportunities it provides to the student community.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Associated Students of Stanford University (ASSU)

        Associated Students of Stanford University

        Mission

        Contact: Ava Brown

        Mission
        The Associated Students of Stanford University was created in 1891 and is the only organization at Stanford of which every student is a member. The ASSU provides funding to over five hundred volunteer student organizations (VSO). These organizations in turn provide the majority of cultural, political, recreational and religious programming for the entire campus. The financial independence that the ASSU affords student organizations is one of the founding principles of the organization.

        The ASSU also works to represent the interests, needs and perspectives of Stanford students at every level of decision making within the university. The ASSU advocates on behalf of Stanford students on issues such as cost of living, diversity, student life and student activities space.

        Each year the ASSU pursues innovative projects and creates new services that will improve the quality of student life offered at Stanford.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • Atma

        Religious

        Mission

        Mission
        The core mission of ATMA is to cultivate a deep understanding that spiritual Awareness is essential for leading a meaningful life a belief that echoes through the diverse tapestry of religious traditions. Through exploring Theology, with a particular focus on Vaishnavism, ATMA aims to illuminate the connection between the soul and the divine. The club embraces Mysticism as a means to support the ultimate aspirations of theology through practices such as devotional singing and mantra chanting as pathways to experiencing a divine connection.

        What sets ATMA apart as a student club is its innovative approach to fostering unity among different spiritual paths through the practice of aligning the soul with the divine and the endeavor of aligning various spiritual practices to unveil their common purpose. This dual concept of Alignment is foundational, offering both a personal path to spiritual growth and a collective exploration of the interconnectedness of diverse spiritual paths.

      • CSA JKA Shotokan of Stanford

        Athletic - Athletic - Martial Arts, Athletic - Club Sport, A3C

        Mission

        Mission
        Shotokan Karate is a weaponless martial art developed in Okinawa and Japan that emphasizes power and efficiency in combat. Skilled karateka defeat their opponents with a minimal number of techniques and effort, which is particularly useful when facing multiple opponents. JKA Shotokan is distinguished from other martial arts by the linearity and strength of its punches, blocks, and kicks. Precise techniques, accompanied by mastery and focus of energy flows and a deep knowledge of the body's vital points, make this karate style a comprehensive system for self-defense and combat.

        Our dojo is a member of the international Japan Karate Association. This means our instruction is based on the teachings of the first pioneers of karate in Japan supplemented by the scientific analysis of later masters at the main dojo. JKA students have access to numerous published resources including books, articles, and YouTube videos. More importantly, your JKA belt rank is recognized in hundreds of dojos all over the United States and the world should you wish to travel and train or move to another city. We strive to train students of all backgrounds as competent practitioners of JKA Shotokan Karate.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

        Mission
        Stanford Club Baseball provides undergraduate and graduate students with an opportunity to play competitive baseball at the sub-varsity level. Through a mix of games and practices, it encourages experienced players to continue to develop their skills to maximize their contributions to the team. The club measures its success in terms of both its on-field production and the level of participation by its members.         Contact: Tania Flores, Antonio Skillicorn, Rosina Lin, Natalia Vasilenok

        Mission
        Flamenco Cardenal strives to cultivate artistic and intellectual community at Stanford centered on flamenco, an art form rooted in the musical traditions of the Romani diaspora, Latin America and the Caribbean, North and West Africa, and Spanish folkloric styles, many of which are of Islamic and Jewish origin. We hold flamenco classes for dancers, singers, and musicians, build relationships with the broader Bay Area flamenco community, organize group outings to local flamenco performances, and host academic lectures and workshops on critical and decolonial flamenco studies. In making Stanford a hub of flamenco culture in the Peninsula, we strive to make amor al arte more accessible to all, to center flamencos legacy as a multiethnic and historically marginalized art form, to uplift unorthodox and innovative approaches to flamenco studies and performance, and to amplify and honor the role of queer, Black, Asian, Chicanx, and Latinx artists in shaping flamencos past and present.

        FSL Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity Incorporated

        Fraternities & Sororities - BCSC

        Mission

        Contact: Jaeden Clark, Email group officers

        Mission
        Kappa Alpha Psi Fraternity, Inc. () is a collegiate Greek-letter fraternity, founded on January 5, 1911 at Indiana University Bloomington. It is the 2nd oldest existing collegiate historically Black Greek letter fraternity and the 1st intercollegiate fraternity incorporated as a national body.The fraternity has over 250,000 members with 700 undergraduate and alumni chapters in every state of the United States, and international chapters in the United Kingdom, Germany, Korea, Japan, the Caribbean, Saint Thomas, Saint Croix, U.S. Virgin Islands, Nigeria, Bermuda, Canada, Dubai, Dominican Republic and South Africa.

        Through its worldwide prominence, Kappa Alpha Psi has had a global impact on events that affect our local communities and places around the globe. Local chapters of Kappa Alpha Psi participate in community outreach activities to feed the homeless, provide scholarships to young people matriculating to college, serve as mentors to young men, participate in blood drives, and serve as hosts of seminars for public health awareness, to name a few. Nationally, Kappa Alpha Psi has provided summer enrichment camps and funds for St. Jude Medical Research Center to assist in the fight against childhood catastrophic diseases by raising more than $1 Million. Internationally, Kappa Alpha Psi members have answered the call to service by proudly serving our military in wars since WWI and raising funds to assist those in need following natural disasters worldwide, including hurricanes, tornadoes, typhoons, and earthquakes.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

        FSL Sigma Phi Epsilon

        Fraternities & Sororities

        Mission

        Group Not Registered Yet

        Mission
        Stanford SigEp's mission is to advance our community values of inclusion, community welfare, and academic and social enrichment. These values guide the totality of our actions from our individual lives to our member interactions to our community engagement and beyond.

        Inclusion

        Community for all. We aim to build and foster a Stanford community actively and intentionally inclusive to all people based on mutual understanding, compassion, and empathy. We recognize the history of elitism and discrimination that has existed in Greek life, and with this in mind we are diligent in dismantling these attitudes and rectifying their past oppression. Our community of inclusion extends from within our chapter into the Stanford community and beyond. To this end, we pursue the following goals:
        Each member's diverse experiences compose an integral part of the chapter. Through elevating their stories, we aim to ensure that all members from their different backgrounds are each other's greatest advocates to succeed and lead in the chapter.
        We strive to deepen our existing relationships and build new bonds with organizations representing BIPOC, FLI, international, and LGBTQ+ students to regularly cosponsor academic, philanthropic, and social events.
        Our community extends beyond Stanford--we seek to grow our commitments to social movements and organizations working for inclusion through fundraising, organizing, and participating.
        Our recruitment priority is on actively appealing to underrepresented students early and consistently and ensuring that we design our fraternity as a space where they see themselves.
        We ensure the continuity and growth of our no-questions-asked dues aid policy. Cost has never been a barrier to SigEp and never will be.

        Community welfare

        All for community. Our organization finds its place within a rich environment of its surrounding communities. In a symbiotic relationship with those around us, we emphasize not only being intentional citizens who support university and fellow organization sponsored events, but also at the same time actively introducing our own sets of initiatives to further community engagement both in a university and local context. As many ResX neighborhoods will be called home by our members, contributing proactively and often to the neighborhood system is a guiding principle for our members. We prioritize these values on an organizational level in order to cultivate personal stewardship among our members in continuously showing communal involvement beyond their time at the university.



        Academic and social enrichment

        We recognize that we each chose Stanford first and foremost to develop our intellects alongside other like minded and bright individuals, and Stanford SigEp positions itself uniquely at the service of this intent. As an organization of students, our chapter affirms its members' wide array of academic interests and supports their academic journeys, placing it front and center. By having all class levels represented within our tight knit community, we aim to offer invaluable mentorship in all spheres, mentorship that extends well beyond one's undergraduate career.

        Forming a solid group of diverse individuals creates opportunities to develop fundamental skills that lend themselves to facets of student life beyond the classroom. The core of our social programming focuses on the personal growth of the individual in an inclusive environment to build lasting bonds and form a lifelong community. To this end, we prohibit pledging and instead ensure that each member carries the same weight as any other. We do not tolerate any ill directed pressure and instead encourage our members towards personal achievement and success. Every one of our sponsored events is set forth with the clear intention towards developing our members as mentally, physically, and emotionally healthy members of the university.

        Membership Benefits

        Lifetime membership

      • GSB Future Of Mobility Club

        GSB (Business School) - Grad

        Mission

        Contact: Email group officers

        Mission
        The purpose of the FOM club is to help GSB students gain a deeper understanding of the rapidly changing mobility landscape that is being disrupted by self-driving and flying cars, new ownership models, and multi-modal transport models. These changes will have an unprecedented effect on hundreds of thousands of jobs in the US economy - and on society as a whole - and at the same time, create new business opportunities for entrepreneurs.

        We will explore the four big trends that are actively challenging the existing infrastructure:

        Connectivity: Cars will be able to communicate with each other, thereby avoiding accidents. What are some key technology trends to make this happen? What skills will be needed for entrepreneurs?
        Autonomy: Cars will be able to drive themselves, which has tremendous effects on various factors such as urban planning, legal codes in case of accidents, insurances, business models for car producers, and new entrants such as Waymo and Uber, etc.
        Sharing: Autonomous cars could be available at the click of a button, thus eliminating the need for personal car ownership. What are the effects on business models of car producers - a USD 2.3 trillion industry in the US alone?
        Electric: Experts agree that the future of the car industry is in electric vehicles. Who will win in the race towards electric mass-mobility? Will it be prominent challengers such as Tesla or the established car producers?

        Membership Benefits

        (2 Years)

        Membership will end on 31 May 2027

      • Healing Strokes

        Community Service - Community Service

        Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Linh Vo

        Mission
        Healing Strokes hopes to facilitate relaxation-based art therapy for stroke patients and their carers with the goal of helping alleviate post-stroke depression often experienced during recovery. Post-stroke depression and related anxiety affects about a third of all stroke survivors, yet many hospitals often lack the proper mental wellness resources needed to address this issue. Under the guidance of neurologist Dr. Nirali Vora and occupational therapist Julie Muccini, we have crafted a relaxation-based art therapy curriculum using an integrated patient-carer team approach. By facilitating creative-art based therapy workshops, we hope undergraduates would be able to gain experience cultivating empathy-based communities, helping to alleviate depressive symptoms among stroke survivors and increasing relief amongst caregivers. We hope to create an undergraduate community that is challenged to engage in discussions of ethical practices both with therapy and with patients as a whole.

        By establishing a welcoming space for creative outlet, Healing Strokes hopes to alleviate depressive symptoms among stroke survivors and provide relief for caregivers.

        Membership Benefits
        Direct clinical experience with patients and access to Stanford medical faculty members.

        Lifetime membership

      • Marine Outreach for Learning and Advocacy in Students

        Community Service

        Mission

        Contact: Stephanie Caddell

        Mission
        Our project directly addresses the critical issue of unequal access to education in specialized fields like marine sciences, which are essential for fostering awareness and solutions for ocean sustainability. Subjects like marine sciences require specialized knowledge, tools, and expertise, often out of reach for students in marginalized schools. This inequity limits their understanding of ocean-related challenges and fuels a vicious cycle of limited opportunity, ultimately hindering efforts to build an ocean-literate society. Our project will bridge this gap through hands-on educational outreach by aligning with SDG 4: Quality Education and the UN Decade of Ocean Sciences Challenge 10. We want to provide engaging and accessible learning experiences that connect school children, especially from marginalized communities, to the oceans. Our oceans sustain life and are under the constant threat of climate change. We will motivate a new generation of ocean-literate citizens to contribute meaningfully to ocean stewardship and sustainable development by supporting a new generation of ocean-literate citizens.

        Mission

        Mission
        The American Constitution Society for Law and Policy is a national organization of law students, law professors, judges, practicing lawyers and others. We want to counter the dominant vision of American law, a narrow conservative vision that lacks appropriate regard for the ways in which the law affects people's lives. We seek to restore the fundamental principles of respect for human dignity, protection of individual rights and liberties, genuine equality, and access to justice to their rightfuland traditionally centralplace in American law.       • SLS Law & Political Economy

        SLS (Law School) - Grad

        Mission

        Mission
        The SLS Law and Political Economy (LPE) group is part of the larger LPE movement, which is a network of scholars, practitioners, and students advancing a legal paradigm rooted in the reality that politics and economics cannot be separatedand that the law is vital in shaping both. LPE centers questions of political economy to confront present-day crises such as regional and racial inequality; ecological devastation; and unaccountable corporate power. The LPE community shares a commitment to mass democracy and an interest in alternatives to the neoliberal economic logic that underlies so many areas of law and policymaking. In that spirit, LPE supports academic work that traces the legal theories that have contributed to our moment, as well as scholarship that proposes new ways to democratize our economy and create a more just, equal, and sustainable future. Check out more about LPE here: lpeproject.org

      • SLS Stanford Plaintiffs' Lawyers Association

        SLS (Law School) - Grad

        Mission

        Mission
        Stanford Law School Plaintiffs' Lawyers Association (PLA) endeavors to build something that has never existed on campus: a community of SLS students and alumni dedicated to contingency-fee based work on behalf of wronged individuals.

        The PLA wil have two purposes:

        First, the PLA will conduct on-campus programming to support student interest in the profession. The PLA will host prominent practitioners to educate students and answer questions about contemporary practice; faculty members to advise student on courses of study, clerkships, and broader developments in the field; and, student panels on summer experiences, future plans and recommendations for success. Ultimately, students interested in the profession will be able to turn to the PLA first for any resource related to the profession information, community support, and guidance, etc. throughout their time at SLS.

        Lastly, the group seeks to build an active and robust alumni network of SLS plaintiffs' lawyers, so that students have a resource for contacting alumni and alumni have a resource to contact each other. Through this work, SLS students and alumni in the field can build and sustain invaluable connections for their professional practice.

      • Stanford Finance

        Pre-professional - Pre-professional

        Mission Membership Benefits

        Mission
        Stanford Finance's mission is to facilitate the entry and success of Stanford students in the finance industry via education, preparation, and the building of a global professional network.

        Membership Benefits
        The finance industry requires know-how, experience, and connections. Each year Stanford Finance accepts a dedicated group of Stanford students into its Analyst Program. The program is made up of four core components:

        1. A workshop series educates the Analysts, prepares them for job applications and interviews, and then teaches them the technical skills they will need once they land jobs.
        2. Networking events enable the Analysts to form professional connections with visiting financial institutions, both bulge-bracket and premier boutique banks. These events also help our analysts find mentors and secure internships, often before traditional, on-campus recruiting begins.
        3. A mentorship program connects each Analyst with a Stanford Finance Officer who will provide private training and advice, and a finance professional, often a Stanford Finance alum, who has been working in the industry for at least several years.
        4. Access to the Alumni Database is vital. Stanford Finance graduates have gone on to lead successful careers. Once a student has been selected to be an analyst, he or she will have access to the alumni database and will gain a lifelong membership in the Stanford Finance community.

        Our Analysts have a history of landing the most competitive internships in the Silicon Valley and on Wall Street. We look for candidates who are disciplined and driven. Above all, we look for candidates who will embody and further Stanford Finance's core values of leadership with integrity and commitment to each other's success.

      • Stanford Mock Trial

        Academic - Academic

        Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Grace Jin, Email group officers

        Mission
        Mock trial is a competitive activity that simulates a trial in court. Every year, hundreds of colleges across the country receive case materials from AMTA (the American Mock Trial Association) and prepare either a civil or criminal case. Each school prepares its own witnesses and attorneys, and then presents their case against other schools in front of judges and scorers who determine the winner. The witnesses answer questions in direct and cross examinations while maintaining character; the attorneys deliver speeches, make objections, and conduct the examinations. It's a public speaking activity (with some law components) that requires thinking on your feet and an ability to improvise.

        Membership Benefits
        While winning is certainly among the highest of our priorities, SMT is a team before anything else. We LOVE our mock family and can't wait for you to be a part of it.

        Lifetime membership

      • Stanford Pre-Law Society

        Pre-professional - Pre-professional

        Mission Membership Benefits

        Contact: Emily Sung, Gracie Sandman, Email group officers

        Mission
        The Stanford Pre-Law Society (SPLS) is a student organization dedicated to bringing together Stanford undergraduates who are interested in the law and in pursuing legal careers. We are a community of like-minded students who wish to help members of the student body reach informed decisions about their futures. Every year we host a diverse program of speaker events, information sessions, and workshops. In addition to programming, we work with Undergraduate Advising and Research (UAR) and other campus organizations to build community, understanding, and a common vision.

        Membership Benefits
        MENTORSHIP

        As one of the premier Pre-Law Societies at Stanford, SPLS offers undergraduates the opportunity to develop relationships with a mentor from Stanford's law school. SPLS offers its members a simple process to find a mentor, as members are only required to fill out a request form to be matched with a current law student. SPLS members are at liberty to communicate with their mentors at their own convenience. Law school mentors serve as a means to learn about law school applications, discover the ins-and-outs of law school, and provide insight on how students can best prepare for graduate school. Alongside 1 v 1 meetings, SPLS will also host a mentor-mentee zoom conference and panel where members can learn from the experience of additional law students.

        LSAT PREP

        Geared at preparing students for a successful application to law school, SPLS hosts recurring LSAT prep sessions organized by TestMasters, an industry leader in test and examination preparation. These sessions are hosted 2-3 times a quarter, free of charge. LSAT prep sessions held by SPLS not only allow students to learn crucial details about the LSAT, but allow students to practice taking the LSAT in real-time, with simulated test environments that closely resemble the real thing. As students ourselves, SPLS membership entails finding suitable times for these sessions to take place, optimizing times and dates where the most students can attend.

        The benefits of becoming a member of the Stanford Pre-Law Society include:

        -Invitations to exclusive, members-only events with lawyers and law professors.
        -Receiving messages our SPLS mailing list with the latest pre-law tips and news, plus event and program highlights, in addition to messages regarding career opportunities.
        -Discounts off of certain LSAT prep courses, practice exams.
        -Eligibility for our mentorship from current Stanford Law School students through the SPLS mentorship program.

      • Stanford Sea Shanty Club

        Mission
        The Stanford Sea Shanty Club brings together fans of sea shanties (naval working songs) for biweekly casual sing-alongs. Long after the heyday of sailing ships, sea shanties continue to have popular appeal, especially since they went viral on TikTok in 2021. At our sing-alongs, we learn and sing sea shanties as well as traditional folk songs, working songs, and songs from other related genres.

        Sea Shanty Club is a place for shanty fans with any level of singing experience (including none) to enjoy singing in a casual environment. (After all, sea shanties were originated by sailors, not professional musicians.) Anyone can come and sing, or just listen along. It is not a choir or a band; there are no commitments to rehearsals or performances. We hope to give shanty fans an immersive way to enjoy this lively genre of music and also introduce sea shanties to a wider audience.

      • Stanford Students for Justice in Palestine

        Social Awareness - Social Awareness

        Mission

        Mission
        1) Students for Justice in Palestine (SJP) is a diverse group of students, faculty, staff, and community members at Stanford University, organized on principles to promote justice, human rights, liberation, and self-determination for the Palestinian people.
        2) SJP is a space comprised of both Palestinian and non-Palestinian students, engaged in self-determination and solidarity, respectively. Within SJP, we defer to the leadership and vision of Palestinian students whenever possible.
        3) SJP views the liberation of the Palestinian people as bound up with the liberation of all oppressed people.
        4) SJP supports a one-state solution for Palestine in which all ethnicities can live under equal rights.
        5) SJP is committed to organizing for the liberation of Palestine from settler colonial rule. This entails a democratic, plurinational one-state solution to initiate the process of decolonization. What we identify decolonization to be composed of includes:
        The right of return for Palestinians and the Palestinian diaspora.
        A process of land reform which adequately addresses the injustice of dispossession and creates the conditions of peace and reconciliation.
        The right to defense and resistance for occupied peoples to survive and demand their sovereignty (per the UN resolution 37/43).
        6) SJP knows that the occupation, apartheid, and colonization of Palestine is a result of U.S/Western imperialism and capitalism. Stanford SJP is committed to understanding and organizing for the liberation of Palestine, and all oppressed peoples, knowing that dismantling systems of oppression such as imperialism and capitalism is at the center of it all. We are committed to peoples struggle around the world and understand the Palestinian struggle to have the potential to inculcate anti-imperialist and anti-capitalist ideology within other US social movements.
        7) SJP acknowledges the land we occupy on Turtle Island, and fights for the liberation of all indigenous peoples globally. Both the US and Israel were founded as European settler colonial outposts, created through the ethnic cleansing of native peoples in order to gain control of maximum land and resources for a white ruling class. Palestinians and Indigenous Populations globally unite and feel the connections in their struggles which are deeply intertwined, which is why it is imperative to understand that Palestine is an Indigenous Struggle, one that we can tangibly support and advocate for.
        8) SJP recognizes the history of settler colonialism in the Americas a history that sees Islamophobia, anti-Indigenous narratives, anti-Blackness, antisemitism, homophobia, ableism, and classism as inextricably bound. Active solidarity is crucial to mobilizing people for global collective livingness, thriving and liberation.

      • Talisman

        Arts - Arts - Music

        Mission

        Contact: Mauricio Alvarez

        Mission
        We are Talisman A Cappella. We were founded on Stanford's campus with an original intention of using music to shed light on underrepresented narratives, especially the music and stories of the Anti-Apartheid movement in South Africa. Every year, as Talisman recreates itself with new voices, we cull the stories that have moved us and formed us, building an ever-expanding repertoire that reflects what is most meaningful to us as individuals and as an ensemble.

        Talisman has had the privilege to perform at several Bay Area Schools, tour in communities in California, the East Coast, the American Southwest, and the Southern United States. We embarked on five tours in South Africa where we have cultivated lasting relationships with several communities and organizations. In 2018, the group took a trip to Maui and Oahu as part of a year dedicated to learning and sharing narratives from the API experience, especially that of Native Hawaiians and their fight for sovereignty and reclamation. In 2019, we flew to Mumbai, and then to Udaipur, India. Ram Sampath, a music composer we met with in Mumbai, said to us: "You don't tolerate each other. You get along...You have to find what unites you and not what divides you." This message was and is timely and important, at home for many of our members in the United States, but also in many regions abroad.


        We have also collaborated with local groups such as An Oakland Storyteller, various Bay Area community gospel choirs, Stanford Taiko, Stanford Everyday People, and numerous other Stanford student groups.

        Talisman as a group is committed not only to education and the arts, but also to social change, equity, and cross-cultural exchange. As we sing, we lend our hearts to uplift, support, remember, and recall the work and wisdom of those who came before us in order to imagine a better world for ourselves and those to come. We invite you to share your voice and your stories with us!

        The mission of the USNDA is to aid in increasing the number of
        minority students entering dental schools, increasing the knowledge of
        dentistry in undergraduate students, and in improving DAT scores of pre-dental undergraduates. Additionally, the USNDA will provide students with the opportunity to visit dental schools and to shadow dentists, as well as to inform students of summer programs and dental research experiences. Records will also be kept of those members accepted into various dental schools.

        Membership Benefits
        -We support tackling health disparities in underserved populations by advocating for a diverse health force.
        -We hope that through networking and mentorship that our students and graduates will attain excellence in all areas
        -As an organization, we task ourselves with programs that are aimed to decrease oral health disparities nation wide.
        -Our aim is to maintain our relationship with NDA, while also fostering mentorship within our organization as well.

      • Women in Mathematics, Statistics, and Computational Engineering

        Academic - Academic, Grad

        Mission

        Mission
        WiMSCE is a student and faculty group established with the aim of retaining graduate women and underrepresented gender minorities in higher education by providing opportunities to interact with their peers and mentors across STEM. The group has chosen these fields as they have a particularly low proportion of women and underrepresented gender minorities. Further, WiMSCE connects members to speakers via lectures spanning academia and industry in the computational sciences, and professional skill coaching with a focus on gender. These types of events will serve to provide WiMSCE members with knowledge and guidance pertaining to professional opportunities and personal challenges faced both during and after graduate school.
